		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Historici, et Jurisconsulti maxim&egrave; pragmatici.
						Justinus, et Neander: cu[m[ Plutarchi vitis; et
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Justin"/>
					<person name="Michael Neander"/>
					<person name="Plutarch"/>
					<book title="Parallel Lives"/>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Gandini Stratagematis: quasi instar
						totius Gra[e]cia[e].
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Marcantonio Gandino"/>
					<book title="Stratagemata"/>
					<location name="Greece"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Historians and lawyers are pragmatists in particular. Justin and Michael Neander: with Plutarch's 'Lives' and Gandino's 'Stratagemata': as if equal to the whole of Greece.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Valor foeminarum.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>The valor of women.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="EN">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						/ Theise boyes dare say to
						your face: Alas, it cannot be in you,
						that is in them. They ar younger,
						bigger, stronger, quicker, or able to endure
						Labour, ritcher, in higher office.
						What predominant, or Equipollent for all these?
						Noman, so continent, hardie, swift, daily daily exercised,
						how erlie refined, as he should be.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						{ Nihil in Rom.
						Historia magis pragmaticum, qu&agrave;m Mithridatis regis.
						Epistola, et Oratio illa apud Salustiu[m]:
						ha[e]c apud Justinum, Libro 38.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Sallust"/>
					<person name="Justin"/>
					<book title="Historiarum Philippicarum libri XLIV"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Nothing in Roman history was more pragmatic than king Mithridates. The epistles and that speech in Sallust: these in Justin, book 38.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						{ Mihi egregi&egrave; conducunt Juliani
						Ca[e]sares: Guicciardini principes quasi depicti:
						Quinctus de petitione Consulatus:
						Marcus de prouincia administranda:
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Cicero"/>
					<person name="Francesco Guicciardini"/>
					<person name="Sallust"/>
					<person name="Plutarch"/>
					<person name="Xenophon"/>
					<book title="De petitione consulatus"/>
					<book title="Epistolae Ciceronis"/>
					<book title="Duae epistolae de republica ordinanda"/>
					<book title="Opuscula"/>
					<book title="Hiero"/>
				</position>
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Sallustius de Rep. ordinanda.
						Plutarchi Politica: Xenophontis Hieron.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>For me, the Julian emperors are extraordinary expedient: portrayed as if Guiccardini's princes: Cicero, to Quintus, 'On running for the consulship': 
			to Marcus, 'On administering the province': <!--JG: Don't get why Marcus is mentioned, since this was a letter to his brother as well?! Will check Harvey's copy in the BL-->
			Sallust, 'On regulating the Republic'. Plutarch's 'Politics': Xenophon's 'On Hiero'.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						Multi egregij, admirabiles, quicquid volunt: sed mihi opus est ad unguem Eutropius, et Suetonius:
						Ca[e]sar, et Tacitus. Aut da Magistros. Justinianum, Bartholu[m], Durandu[m]; et
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Flavius Eutropius"/>
					<person name="Suetonius"/>
					<person name="Julius Caesar"/>
					<person name="Tacitus"/>
					<person name="Justinian"/>
					<person name="Bartolus de Saxoferrato"/>
					<person name="Guillaume Durand"/>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						Politicu[m] tande[m] Pragmaticu[m] Bodinu[m] meu[m].
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Jean Bodin"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Many extraordinary and admirable people wish whatever: but for me it is useful to learn by heart Eutropius, and Suetonius; Caesar and Tacitus. Or bestow to magistrates. Justinian, Bartholus, and
			Durand; and finally my political pragmatist Bodin.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian" marginalia_id="Ha2.188r_0001" marginalia_continues_to="Ha2.187v_0001" marginalia_to_transcription="Ha2.187v.xml" book_id="FolgersHa2">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						Necessaria etiam ad unguem Althusij ars Juris propter memoriam: Hopperi ciuilis ratio propter
						illuminatu[m] discursum: Vigelij repertorium, et ius controuersum propter expeditam, certamq[ue] Praxin:
							<!-- Continues onto facing page, right margin, Ha2.187v -->
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Johannes Althusius"/>
					<person name="Joachim Hoppers"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>It is also necessary to memorise by heart Althusius' art of law by means of memory: Hopper's civil reason by means of illuminated discourse:
			Virgil's repertoire and the legal compilation by means of expediency and certain praxis:</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
